'''Mure Shrine''' (むれじんじゃ; simplified characters: '''牟礼神社''') is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Ibaraki City|Q502403|qid=Q502403|1=Ibaraki, Osaka}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|qid=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and under the {{ill|lt=modern system of shrine ranks|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was classified as a {{ill|lt=Village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Takehaya Susanoo no Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} (たてはやすさのおのみこと)
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Koyane no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}} (あめのこやねのみこと)

=== History ===
In the mid-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' lists it as “Mure Shrine, {{ill|lt=Shimashimo District|Q10976940|qid=Q10976940|1=Shimashimo district}}, Settsu Province,” and it is ranked as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.

In the ''{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|qid=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}'', in the section on {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|qid=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}}, there is the passage “Miko Ōnakatsuhiko no Mikoto is the ancestral deity of Mure no Wake,” leading to a theory that the shrine originally enshrined {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōnakatsuhiko no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}} (おおなかつひこのみこと), the ancestor of the Mure clan.<ref>However, the relationship between “Mure no Wake” and this locality is not clear (from the “Mure Village” entry in ''Place Names of Osaka Prefecture'').</ref> Nevertheless, it is said that in order to avoid the temple and shrine burnings carried out by {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|qid=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}}, the shrine falsely claimed its enshrined deities were {{ill|lt=Gozu Tennō|Q11570247|qid=Q11570247|1=Gozu Tennō}} and the {{ill|lt=Kasuga deities|Q11088805|qid=Q11088805|1=Kasuga-no-Kami}}, whom Nobunaga revered, and this claim remained thereafter.

In {{ill|lt=Hōei|Q1145262|qid=Q1145262|1=Hōei}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1704|Q6824|qid=Q6824|1=1704}}), it was returned from the Mure settlement to the Nakamura settlement.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), under the {{ill|lt=modern system of shrine ranks|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, it was designated a {{ill|lt=Village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 14 ({{ill|lt=1939|Q18639|qid=Q18639|1=1939}}), due to river improvement works on the {{ill|lt=Ai River|Q11450512|qid=Q11450512|1=Ai River}}, the shrine was relocated to its present site. In Shōwa 15 ({{ill|lt=1940|Q18633|qid=Q18633|1=1940}}), it received and repurposed the building of the north-facing Hachiman Shrine, a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|lt=Ikukunitama Shrine|Q11574477|qid=Q11574477|1=Ikukunitama Shrine}}, which had been built in {{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 11 ({{ill|lt=1606|Q6747|qid=Q6747|1=1606}}) by {{ill|lt=Katagiri Katsumoto|Q1882775|qid=Q1882775|1=Katagiri Katsumoto}}, as its shrine hall. In Shōwa 54 ({{ill|lt=1979|Q2484|qid=Q2484|1=1979}}), the main hall was restored.

